            <fr:title text="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group › Étale morphisms › Étale covers of a normal scheme"><fr:link type="local" href="sga1-i.xml" addr="sga1-i" title="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group › Étale morphisms"><fr:link type="local" href="sga1.xml" addr="sga1" title="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group">SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group</fr:link> › Étale morphisms</fr:link> › Étale covers of a normal scheme</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Section</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>I.10</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>sga1-i</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>282</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> be normal and connected of field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a separated étale prescheme over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the connected components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_i]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> are integral, their fields <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i]]></fr:tex> are finite separable extensions of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_i]]></fr:tex> can be identified with a non-empty open subset of the normalisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i]]></fr:tex> (and thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> with a dense open subset of the normalisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R(X)=L=\prod  K_i]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R(X)]]></fr:tex> is the ring of rational functions on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>280</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#273</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-273.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.10.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>By <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.9.10" href="sga1-i.9.10.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="I.9.10" />, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is normal, and a fortiori its local rings are integral, and so the connected components of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> are irreducible.
      Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_i]]></fr:tex> is normal, and also finite and dominant over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, it follows from a particular (almost trivial, actually) case of the Main Theorem that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_i]]></fr:tex> is an open subset of the normalisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> in the field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_i]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>283</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Under the conditions of <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.1" href="sga1-i.10.1.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.1" />, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> (i.e. an étale cover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>) if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to the normalisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L=R(X)]]></fr:tex> (the ring of rational functions on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>284</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#274</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-274.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.10.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We know that this normalisation is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> (since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is normal, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R/K]]></fr:tex> separable);
      conversely, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, then it is also finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex>, and so its image in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> is closed (and it is also dense).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>An algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> of finite rank over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em>unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex></fr:em> (or simply <fr:em>unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex></fr:em> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is evident) if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is a separable algebra over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> (i.e. a direct sum of separable extensions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i]]></fr:tex>) <fr:em>and</fr:em> the normalisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> (i.e. the disjoint sum of the normalisations of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> in the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i]]></fr:tex>) is unramified (i.e. étale, by <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.9.11" href="sga1-i.9.11.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="I.9.11" />) over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
  Thus:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>285</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> that is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> and such that every irreducible component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> dominates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R(X)]]></fr:tex> be the ring of rational functions on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> (given by the product of the local rings of the generic points of the irreducible components of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>), so that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\mapsto  R(X)]]></fr:tex> is a functor, with values in algebras of finite rank over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K=R(Y)]]></fr:tex>.
    Then this functor establishes an equivalence between the category of connected étale covers of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> and the category of extensions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> that are unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>286</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#275</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-275.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.10.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The inverse functor is the normalisation functor.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is affine, and thus defined by a normal ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> with field of fractions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>.
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> be a finite extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> given by a direct sum of fields.
      Then, by definition, the normalisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}(A')]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex> is the normalisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>.
      To say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> implies that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex> is unramified (or even étale) over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is local, then it is equivalent to say that the local rings <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A'_\mathfrak {n}]]></fr:tex> (where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {n}]]></fr:tex> runs over the finite set of maximal ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex>, i.e. the prime ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex> that induce the maximal ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {m}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>) are unramified (i.e. étale) over the local ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
      Finally, note that the discriminant criterion of <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.4.10" href="sga1-i.4.10.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.4.10" /> can also be applied to this situation
      (more generally, a variant of the aforementioned criterion can be stated thusly, without any preliminary flatness condition when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> dominates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, but with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> still assumed to be locally integral: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B\to  B\otimes _A K]]></fr:tex> are injective — then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {tr}_{L/K}]]></fr:tex> is defined — and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {tr}_{L/K}(xy)]]></fr:tex> induces a <fr:em>fundamental bilinear form</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B\times  B\to  A]]></fr:tex>, i.e. there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_i\in  B]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1\leq  i\leq  n=\operatorname {rank}_K L]]></fr:tex>) such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {tr}(x_ix_j)\in  A]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i,j]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (\operatorname {tr}(x_i x_j))_{1\leq  i,j\leq  n}]]></fr:tex> is invertible in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>The syllogism <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.4.6" href="sga1-i.4.6.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.4.6" /> immediately implies the syllogism of being unramified in the classical case:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>287</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.4</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> be a normal integral prescheme, of field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>.
    Then</fr:p>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;i. &quot;">
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;ii. &quot;">
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is an extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> that is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> is a normal prescheme, of field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>, that dominates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> (e.g. the normalisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>), and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> an extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> that is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M/K]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> (this is the <fr:em>transitivity</fr:em> property).
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;iii. &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> be a normal integral prescheme that dominates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, of field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K'/K]]></fr:tex>;
      if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is an extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> that is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L\otimes _K K']]></fr:tex> is an extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K']]></fr:tex> that is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> (this is the <fr:em>translation</fr:em> property).
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Furthermore:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>292</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.5</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Under the conditions of (iii) in <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.4" href="sga1-i.10.4.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.4" />, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y=\operatorname {Spec}(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y'=\operatorname {Spec}(A')]]></fr:tex>, then the normalisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {A'}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L'=L\otimes _K K']]></fr:tex> can be identified with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {A}\otimes _A A']]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {A}]]></fr:tex> is the normalisation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Usually, people (those who are disgusted by the consideration of non-integral rings, even if they are direct sums of fields) state the translation property in the following (weaker) form:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>293</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.6</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Under the conditions of (iii) in <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.4" href="sga1-i.10.4.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.4" />, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_1]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:em>sum extension</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L/K]]></fr:tex> (unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>) and of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K'/K]]></fr:tex>.
    Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_1/K']]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex>.
    In the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y=\operatorname {Spec}(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y'=\operatorname {Spec}(A')]]></fr:tex>, we further have that
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \bar {A'} = A[\bar {A},A']     ]]></fr:tex>
    i.e. the normalisation ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {A'}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L_1]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-algebra generated by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A']]></fr:tex> and by the normalisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {A}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>This latter fact is actually false without the unramified hypothesis, even in the case of extensions given by direct sums of number fields...</fr:p>
            <fr:p>To finish this section, we are going to give the intuitive interpretation of the notion of étale covers: there should be the "maximal number" of points over the point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  Y]]></fr:tex> in question, and, in particular, there should not be "multiple points combined" over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.
  To prove results in this sense, in all desirable generality, we will assume here <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.7" href="sga1-i.10.7.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.7" /> found below (whose proof will be given in the multiplodoque, Chapter IV, Section 15, and uses Chevalley's technique of constructible sets, and a little bit of the theory of descent...).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A morphism of finite type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em>universally open</fr:em> if, for every base extension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y'\to  Y]]></fr:tex> (with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> locally Noetherian), the morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f'\colon  X'=X\times _Y Y'\to  Y']]></fr:tex> is open, i.e. sends open subsets to open subsets.
  We can actually restrict to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> is of finite type over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> (and even to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> is of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y[t_1,\ldots ,t_r]]]></fr:tex>, where the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t_i]]></fr:tex> are indeterminates).
  A universally open morphism is a fortiori open (but the converse is false);
  on the other hand, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is open, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> are irreducible, then all of the components of all of the fibres of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> are of the same dimension (i.e. the dimension of the generic fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(z)]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> is the generic point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>).
  Finally, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is normal, then this latter condition already implies that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>universally</fr:em> open (Chevalley's theorem).
  It thus follows, for example, that, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em>quasi-finite</fr:em> morphism, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> normal and irreducible, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is universally open (or even open) if and only if every irreducible component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> dominates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
  Recall also that a flat morphism (of finite type) is open, and thus also universally open.
  With these preliminaries, "recall" the following:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>294</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.7</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> be a quasi-finite, separated, universally open morphism.
    For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  Y]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y)]]></fr:tex> be the "geometric number of points in the fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(y)]]></fr:tex>", equal to the sum of the separable degrees of the residue extensions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k(x)/k(y)]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> runs over the points of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(y)]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\mapsto  n(y)]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is upper semi-continuous.
    For it to be constant on a neighbourhood of the point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> (i.e. for it to be the case that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y)=n(z_i)]]></fr:tex>, where the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_i]]></fr:tex> are the generic points of the irreducible components of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> that contain <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>), it is necessary and sufficient for there to exist a neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X|U]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>finite</fr:em> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>.
    (cf. EGA IV 15.5.1.)</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>295</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.8</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.8.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.8</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\mapsto  n(y)]]></fr:tex> is constant, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is geometrically unibranch(For the definition, cf. <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.11" href="sga1-i.11.xml" taxon="Section" number="I.11" />), then the irreducible components of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> are disjoint.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>296</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.9</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.9.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.9</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> be a separated <fr:em>étale</fr:em> morphism.
    With the notation of <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.7" href="sga1-i.10.7.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.7" />, the function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mapsto  n(y)]]></fr:tex> is upper semi-continuous.
    For it to be constant on a neighbourhood of the point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> (i.e. for it to be the case that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y)=n(z_i)]]></fr:tex>, where the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_i]]></fr:tex> are the generic points of the irreducible components of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> that contain <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>), it is necessary and sufficient that there exist a neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X|U]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>finite</fr:em> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>, i.e. such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X|U]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:em>étale cover</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>297</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.10</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.10.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.10</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>For a separated étale morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> (with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> connected) to be finite (i.e. for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> to make <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> an <fr:em>étale cover</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>), it is necessary and sufficient that all the fibres of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> have the same geometric number of points.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.7" href="sga1-i.10.7.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.7" /> and its corollary (<fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.8" href="sga1-i.10.8.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="I.10.8" />), there was no normality hypothesis on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>;
  if we make such a hypothesis, then we find the following stronger statement (which is usually taken as the definition of unramified for a cover):</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>298</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.11</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.11.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.11</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> be a separated <fr:em>quasi-finite</fr:em> morphism.
    Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>irreducible</fr:em>, that every component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> dominates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is reduced (i.e. that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_X]]></fr:tex> has no nilpotent elements).
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> be the degree of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> (i.e. the sum of the degrees, over the field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, of the fields <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i]]></fr:tex> of the irreducible components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_i]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>).
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> be a normal point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the geometric number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y)]]></fr:tex> of points of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq  n]]></fr:tex>, with equality if and only if there exists an open neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X|U]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:em>étale cover</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>299</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#276</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-276.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.10.11</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The "only if" is trivial;
      we will prove the "if".
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> be the generic point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
      Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(z)]]></fr:tex>, which is equal to the sum of the separable degrees of the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K_i/K]]></fr:tex>, is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq  n]]></fr:tex>, and, by <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.7" href="sga1-i.10.7.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="I.10.7" />, we have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y)\leq  n(z)]]></fr:tex>;
      thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y)\leq  n]]></fr:tex>, with equality implying that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X|U]]></fr:tex> if <fr:em>finite</fr:em> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>, for some suitable neighbourhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.
      We can thus suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and that the function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n(y')]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is constant.
      Then, by <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.10.8" href="sga1-i.10.8.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="I.10.8" />, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is the disjoint union of its irreducible components, and so, to prove that it is unramified at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>, we can restrict to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is irreducible, thus integral.
      Finally, we can assume that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y=\operatorname {Spec}(\mathcal {O}_y)]]></fr:tex>.
      The theorem thus reduces to the following classical statement:</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>300</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.10.12</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.10.12.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.10.12</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.10</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be a normal local ring (Noetherian, as always), of field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>;
    let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> be a finite extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, and of separable degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n_s]]></fr:tex>;
    let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> be a sub-ring of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> that is finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, with field of fraction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>;
    let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {m}]]></fr:tex> be the maximal ideal of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n']]></fr:tex> the separable degree of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B/\mathfrak {m}B]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/\mathfrak {m}A=k]]></fr:tex> (which is equal to the sum of the separable deprees of the residue extensions of this ring).
    Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n'\leq  n_s]]></fr:tex>, and a fortiori <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n'\leq  n]]></fr:tex>.
    This latter inequality is an equality if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is unramified (i.e. étale) over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>301</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#277</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-277.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.10.12</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>It remains only to show that, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n'=n]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is étale over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
      Recall the proof in the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> is infinite:
      we need only show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R=B/\mathfrak {m}B]]></fr:tex> is separable over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>;
      if this were not the case, then it would follow (by a known lemma) that there exists an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> whose minimal polynomial over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> is of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[>n']]></fr:tex>.
      This element would come from an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, whose minimal polynomial over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> (as an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>) is of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq  n]]></fr:tex>;
      but this minimal polynomial has coefficients in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is normal, and thus gives, by restriction modulo <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {m}]]></fr:tex>, a monic polynomial <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F\in  k[t]]]></fr:tex> of degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq  n=n']]></fr:tex>, such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F(a)=0]]></fr:tex>.
      But this is a contradiction.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>In the general case (where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> can be finite), we can again use geometric language:
      we consider <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y'=\operatorname {Spec}(A[t])]]></fr:tex>, which is faithfully flat over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and the generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y']]></fr:tex> of the fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}(k[t])]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.
      Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X'=X\times _Y Y'=\operatorname {Spec}(B[t])]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y']]></fr:tex>, as we immediately see.
      On the other hand, by the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y']]></fr:tex>, its residue field is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k(t)]]></fr:tex>, and thus infinite.
      Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y']]></fr:tex> is a normal point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y']]></fr:tex>, we are now in the previous case.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
